bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The University Marshal reports to the Executive Vice President for Academic Affairs, and oversees official functions at the University, such as commencements, the conferring of honorary degrees, opening convocation for the school year, and other special ceremonies. Robert Jones, professor of Religion, held the post for twenty years, from 1969-89, during which time the ceremonial mace came into use (1981). Before him, John Latimer, professor of Classics, served in the position from 1953-69. N.B. This history note was written in 2005

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include commencement programs, budgets, scripts, and videotapes. They range in date from 1825 to 2005 and were transferred to the University Archives by the University Marshal. Note that not all series have been processed. Please ask staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in four series: Convocation records; Programs and addresses; Office files; and Commencements and convocations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series includes records from commencements and convocations. It includes programs, budgets, memorial services, videotapes, scripts, and speakers. They range in date from 1971-1989.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains schedules, addresses, biographical information, memorandums, lists, newspapers, correspondence, invitations, and forms. They range in date from 1825 to 2005. They concern The George Washington University's commencements and honorary degree holders. One newspaper is in Farsi.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of commencement and convocation scripts, honorary degrees and award files, correspondence, and diagrams for university yard and Constituion Hall seating for graduations. There is no arrangement scheme. They range in date from 1969-87, and were transferred to the University Archives in 1998.
